Furthering this followup, would you have any suggestion on how to recover from this?  Is it possible to manually copy the files from the system partition back into the data partition?  Thanks again.
replyContent: It seems that cleaned-up apps have their databases security context reset to a system context incorrectly upon reboot. The idea is to reset it to u:object_r:app_data_file:s0. Either one of these shell commands should do it: restorecon -r -F /data/data or chcon u:object_r:app_data_file:s0 /data/data/*/databases/*.

replyContent: You might want to review the screen off settings you applied as they can cause unlock lags. I had to update my review.  If I could give this app TEN stars I would.  If it was TWENTY bucks I'd pay it.  It is simply the best app I've ever used for Android.  I use it on every device I own.  What prompted me to edit the review is this - Last night I flashed a new ROM (Android 4.2) on my tablet.  It was a new kernel as well.  I didn't like it and tried to go back to my old ROM.  Not happening... I thought I'd bricked my tablet.   After a complete factory reset I finally got the OS running... of course there were no apps.  Since I am always trying the "latest" and "greatest" I've gotten used to re-downloading and reinstalling everything.  But as I got started I remembered AT.  I downloaded it, installed it, hit "One Click" restore and in six minutes EVERY app I had before was restored and working perfectly.  I know there are a lot of backup restore apps..  But AT takes care of everything for me.  I can tweak anything from CPU speed to individual lines in the build and sysctl files.. or there are dozens of tweaks and presets.  BEST F-ING APP EVER!
Works great on N10 and N4... Didn't buy the individual pro apps over the years it's been around... but once combined it makes more sense now... And I NEVER have paid this much for android app b4!
